2. Data information

2.1 Number of rows

dim(df)[1]
[1] 1599

2.2 Number of columns

dim(df)[2]
[1] 12

2.3 Column names

colnames(df)
 [1] "fixed.acidity"        "volatile.acidity"     "citric.acid"         
 [4] "residual.sugar"       "chlorides"            "free.sulfur.dioxide" 
 [7] "total.sulfur.dioxide" "density"              "pH"                  
[10] "sulphates"            "alcohol"              "quality"

2.3.1 Column names explenation

fixed.acidity - most acids involved with wine
volatile.acidity - the amount of acetic acid in wine
citric.acid - citric acid can add â€˜freshnessâ€™ and flavor to wines
residual.sugar - the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops
chlorides - the amount of salt in the wine
free.sulfur.dioxide - the free form of SO2
total.sulfur.dioxide - amount of free and bound forms of S02
density - density, the density of wine is close to that of water
pH - escribes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic)
sulphates - a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels
alcohol - the percent alcohol content of the wine
quality - output variable (based on sensory data, score between 0 and 10)

3. Missing data

vis_miss(df, sort_miss = TRUE, cluster = TRUE)

4. Variable distribution and summary

4.0 Summary explanation

Min - minimum value
1st Qu. - First quantile
Median - median
Mean - mean
3rd Qu. - Third quantile
Max - maximum value

5. Dependences of two variables

5.1 Alcohol and density

ggplot(df,aes(x=alcohol,y=density))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")+
  labs(title = "How does density depend on alcohol?")

The higher the alcohol level the lower the density. The most popular alcohol level is between 9 and 11 percent, while the density is similar to waterâ€™s density at 0.9975 kg/dm^3.

5.2 Residual sugar and density

ggplot(df,aes(x=residual.sugar,y=density))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method="lm")+
  labs(title = "How does density depend on residual sugar?")

The higher the residual sugar level the higher the density. The most popular residual sugar is about 3.

5.3 Chlorides and pH

ggplot(df,aes(x=chlorides,y=pH))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")+
  labs(title = "How does pH depend on chlorides?")

The higher the chlorides level the lower the pH. The most popular chlorides level is about 0.08.

5.4 Quality and alcohol

ggplot(df,aes(x=factor(quality),y=alcohol))+
  geom_violin()+
  labs(title = "How does alcohol depend on quality?",
       x="quality")

Generally the better the quality the higher the alcohol level. For the lower quality(3-5) alcohol level stands at about 9-10 percent.
